# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1820-state-of-the-union-address
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/16th-united-states-congress] The **16th United States Congress** was a meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government, consisting of the United States Senate and the United States House of Representatives.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/16th-united-states-congress] It met in Washington, D.C. from March 4, 1819, to March 4, 1821, during the third and fourth years of James Monroe's presidency.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/16th-united-states-congress] The apportionment of seats in the House of Representatives was based on the 1810 United States census.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/16th-united-states-congress] Both chambers had a Democratic-Republican majority.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/16th-united-states-congress] The count below identifies party affiliations at the beginning of the first session of this congress.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/16th-united-states-congress] Changes resulting from subsequent replacements are shown below in the "Changes in membership" section.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/16th-united-states-congress] During this congress, two Senate seats were added for each of the new states of Alabama and Maine.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/16th-united-states-congress] During this congress, one House seat was added for the new state of Alabama and one seat was reapportioned from Massachusetts to the new state of Maine.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/16th-united-states-congress] For the beginning of the next congress, six more seats from Massachusetts would be reapportioned to Maine.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/16th-united-states-congress] This list is arranged by chamber, then by state.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/16th-united-states-congress] Senators are listed by class and representatives are listed by district.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/16th-united-states-congress] Senators were elected by the state legislatures every two years, with one-third beginning new six-year terms with each Congress.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/16th-united-states-congress] Preceding the names in the list below are Senate class numbers, which indicate the cycle of their election.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/16th-united-states-congress] In this Congress, Class 1 meant their term ended with this Congress, requiring re-election in 1820; Class 2 meant their term began in the last Congress, requiring re-election in 1822; and Class 3 meant their term began in this Congress, requiring re-election in 1824.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/16th-united-states-congress] The count below reflects changes from the beginning of this Congress.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/16th-united-states-congress] There were 5 resignations, 2 deaths, 2 vacancies before the Congress, and 4 new seats.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/16th-united-states-congress] The Democratic-Republicans had a 7-seat net gain and the Federalists had a 1-seat net loss.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/16th-united-states-congress] There were 13 resignations, 5 deaths, 2 contested elections, and 2 new seats.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/16th-united-states-congress] The Democratic-Republicans had a 1-seat net gain and the Federalists had no net change.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/16th-united-states-congress] Lists of committees and their party leaders.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The first election for Virginia's 5th congressional district took place on February 2, 1789, for a two-year term to commence on March 4 of that year.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] In a race that turned on the candidates' positions on the need for amendments (the Bill of Rights) to the recently ratified U.S.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Constitution, James Madison defeated James Monroe for a place in the House of Representatives of the First Congress.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] It is the only congressional election in U.S. history in which two future presidents opposed each other.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] They put forward Monroe, a young but experienced politician who was a war hero wounded at the 1776 Battle of Trenton, as a candidate for the seat.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Monroe did not seek the contest, but once drafted campaigned vigorously.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Despite bitterly cold weather, the two candidates debated outdoors; traveling after one such meeting, Madison suffered frostbite on his face.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Although Madison had earlier stated that amendments to the Constitution were not necessary, during the campaign he took the position that they were, but should be proposed by Congress, rather than by an Article V Convention that Anti-Federalists such as Monroe and Henry supported.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison won the election comfortably, to the satisfaction of his supporters such as President-elect George Washington.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The race did not affect Madison's friendship with Monroe, who was elected to the Senate in 1790, and who would serve as Madison's Secretary of State and succeed him as president in 1817.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] James Madison was born on March 16, 1751 (March 5, 1750, Old Style), at the Belle Grove plantation near Port Conway, Virginia.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He grew up on his parents' estate of Montpelier, and was involved in politics from a young age, serving on the local Committee of Safety at age 23.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He represented Orange County in the Fifth Virginia Convention of 1776.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] After service on the Virginia Council of State, where he forged a lifelong friendship with Governor Thomas Jefferson, he was elected to the Second Continental Congress becoming its youngest member.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He was one of Virginia's delegates to the Constitutional Convention in 1787, and helped persuade General George Washington to be its chair, which gave the convention the moral authority to propose a new plan of government.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He was the originator of the Virginia Plan that became the basis of the federal government proposed by the convention.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] James Monroe was born April 28, 1758, in Westmoreland County, Virginia, the son of prosperous planters, Spence Monroe and Elizabeth Jones Monroe.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] By 1774, the year he entered the College of William & Mary, both his parents had died.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] In early 1776, he joined the Virginia militia and became an officer in the Continental Army, later that year being severely wounded at the Battle of Trenton.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He left Continental service in 1779, and was made a colonel in the state militia.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] After the war, Monroe studied law under Jefferson and was elected to the House of Delegates in 1782, and to the Congress of the Confederation in New York in 1783, where he sought to expand the powers of that body.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] In 1784, Madison was told by Jefferson that Monroe wanted to begin a correspondence with him, beginning a relationship that would last until Monroe's death in 1831.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The two men differed over whether their state should ratify the Constitution at the Virginia Ratifying Convention, with Madison in favor and Monroe against.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Opponents deemed the proposed national government to be too powerful, and many wanted a second constitutional convention in order to place limits on it.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Despite their efforts, Virginia narrowly ratified the Constitution on June 25, 1788.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Monroe, like Jefferson, believed that there needed to be a Bill of Rights protecting fundamental liberties from infringement by the new federal government.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Ratification had not been a major issue in the Virginia legislative elections of 1788, since it was expected to be decided by the Ratifying Convention that had just been chosen by the voters.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] When the General Assembly convened in October 1788, though, it had a majority of Anti-Federalist members, and was led by Henry, a member of the House of Delegates for Prince Edward County.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Henry sought to avenge the Anti-Federalist defeat at the Ratifying Convention, and also believed Madison would not seek amendments, or would do so in a lukewarm fashion.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] On October 31, the General Assembly re-elected Madison to his seat in the lame-duck Confederation Congress, a body that would cease to exist with the coming of the new federal government.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Henry's motives in allowing this are uncertain, with some historians stating it was to keep Madison in New York, far from the elections for Congress taking place in Virginia.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Historian Chris DeRose hypothesizes that Madison's seat there was his if he wanted it, and his acceptance meant that he expected to remain in New York (where the new Congress would convene) and win his seat in Virginia without needing to campaign.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison, who sought election to the House of Representatives, yielded to Washington and the Federalist minority in the legislature and allowed his name to be put forward in the legislature's election for Virginia's two U.S. senators—until 1913, senators were elected by the state legislatures.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Henry nominated two Anti-Federalists, Richard Henry Lee and William Grayson, while Madison was the sole Federalist named.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Henry told the General Assembly that Madison was "unworthy of the confidence of the people" and that his election "would terminate in producing rivulets of blood throughout the land".
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Henry's nominees were elected, Lee with 98 votes and Grayson with 86, while the defeated Madison gained 77.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The General Assembly turned its attention to dividing the state into congressional districts.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison's home county, Orange, was placed in a district with seven others, five of which had elected representatives to the Ratifying Convention who had opposed ratification, while Orange and one other had voted in favor and one county's delegation had split its vote.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The General Assembly required that candidates live in the district, a qualification not found in the federal Constitution.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Fauquier County, closely associated with Orange both geographically and economically, had supported ratification, but was excluded despite the efforts of Federalists.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Despite some stating that Henry had contrived a district in which Madison was sure to be defeated, Thomas Rogers Hunter in a journal article examined the question, and concluded, "the district was compact and bounded on all sides by natural geographic features.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Simply put, Patrick Henry did not attempt to gerrymander James Madison out of a seat in the first U.S.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Congress." Virginia's 5th congressional district consisted of the counties of Albemarle, Amherst, Culpeper, Fluvanna, Goochland, Louisa, Orange and Spotsylvania.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Some of these counties were later divided, so the district that Madison contested also included the present-day counties of Greene, Madison, Nelson and Rappahannock.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] French Strother, a long-time Virginia legislator from Culpeper County who had opposed ratification at the Virginia Convention, was solicited as a candidate to oppose Madison, but declined.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] William Cabell, of Amherst County, was also considered as an Anti-Federalist candidate but Monroe was selected instead.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Both Strother and Cabell threw their support behind Monroe.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] A resident of Spotsylvania County, Monroe was reluctant to run against his friend Madison, but was probably encouraged by Henry, George Mason and other Anti-Federalists, though discouraged by his uncle, Joseph Jones.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] His service in the Revolutionary War, and his political service after it, were electoral assets.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The selection of Monroe was enough to worry Washington: "Sorry indeed should I be if Mr.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Federalist Henry Lee wrote to him, "I profess myself pleased with your exclusion from the senate & I wish it may so happen in the lower house [in which case] you will be left qualified to take part in the administration, which is the place proper for you".
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Nevertheless, Henry Lee believed Madison would win, calling Monroe "the beau".
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison disliked electioneering, but realized he would have to campaign hard to win the race.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The Fifth District race would be the only congressional election in history to oppose two future U.S. presidents.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The largest issue in the campaign was the question of a Bill of Rights protecting personal freedoms as amendments to the Constitution.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison's view had been that these were unnecessary as the Federal government had only limited power and that in any event, the new government should be allowed to operate for a time before changes were made to the Constitution.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] To take such a stance in the campaign would be political suicide, and Madison recognized that there was widespread support for such amendments.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] But he felt it to be important that Congress proposed them, believing that route to be a quicker, easier, and safer means of passage than an Article V convention, which was favored by the Anti-Federalists such as Monroe.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Nevertheless, he was skeptical about the effect of such amendments, calling them "parchment barriers", ineffective if the Federal government was determined to bypass them.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He told the voters that if elected, he would work diligently for the passage of a Bill of Rights.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison's earlier stances made it easy to depict him in this light.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison's pledge to support a Bill of Rights if elected left the question of direct taxation as the major difference between them.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Monroe believed the power of the Federal government to directly tax the citizens to be not only unnecessary, but injurious to American liberty.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He felt the government could raise money by tariffs, by the sale of public lands, or by borrowing.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison responded that were the Federal government unable to tax citizens directly, tariffs would be the major source of revenue, and this would disproportionately hurt the South, which had few manufactures and imported heavily from overseas.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He also stated that having federal taxes paid in each state would help bind the nation together as giving each a financial stake in the Union's success.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison had been in New York, helping to wrap up the affairs of the old Congress of the Confederation.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He received letters from other parts of Virginia from those who believed the residency requirement unconstitutional, offering to have him run there, but he preferred to run in his home district, and he declined.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] A trip to Virginia on horseback or in a carriage would be personally hard on Madison, then suffering from a bad case of hemorrhoids.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] On December 8, 1788, he wrote to Jefferson (who was in Paris) that he would return to Virginia to campaign for his election, a decision prompted in part by warnings from Virginians that he could not win without personally fighting for the seat.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He arrived at Washington's plantation, Mount Vernon, on December 18, for a visit that lasted until he returned home to Orange County and his estate, Montpelier, just after Christmas.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] From the time Madison arrived in Virginia, the weather was unusually cold and snowy; the candidates often had to speak in freezing conditions, and the last weekend before the election saw 10 inches (250 mm) of snow.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Aware he was not an orator of Henry's quality, Madison launched a letter-writing campaign, advocating for the new Constitution; though initially taken by surprise, Monroe also set out his positions in letters.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] It was Madison's intent, in writing to key citizens in each community, both to enlist support, and have the recipients circulate the letters locally or publish them in local newspapers.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] For Monroe's part, according to DeRose, he "poured himself into the campaign with frenetic energy, determined to campaign everywhere, to personally engage voters, and to make liberal use of his pen to correspond with community leaders.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Considering him as being able to render his Country Great Services on this important occasion".
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] On January 7, 1789, Virginians chose electors who would vote for the first U.S. president.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The districts for this were not coextensive with congressional districts, since Virginia was entitled to 12 electors but only 10 congressmen.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Still, six of the counties in the Fifth District were in the same district for choosing an elector, and the race featured a Federalist and Anti-Federalist, though both were pledged to vote for Washington for president.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Goochland and Louisa counties were not in that electoral district, but Buckingham County was.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The Federalist, Edward Stevens, was elected, and outpolled his opponent within the Fifth District, but both parties took hope from the result, with the Anti-Federalists cheered by the fact that Stevens had easily taken Spotsylvania County, where the local favorite Monroe would presumably do better.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The candidates sought to appeal to the local religious communities, of which the Baptists were the most influential.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] That community had taken the position that the Constitution did not provide sufficient protection for their religious liberty.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison's pledge of support for amendments defused much of the Anti-Federalist anger against him.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The two men were quite friendly with each other, and decided to travel together between debates, riding from courthouse to courthouse, making speeches before large crowds.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] These debates showed the physical contrast between the tall, athletic Monroe, who had a full head of brown hair, and the short, slender Madison and his receding hairline.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] They often rode together, ate together, and lodged in the same room.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] In 18th century Virginia, Court Day, a different day in each local county, was not only an opportunity for lawyers and judges to try cases, but a social gathering, including fairs, markets, and other events.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The candidates addressed those present, sometimes speaking for hours to the largest crowds they were likely to find during the campaign.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Henry Lee wrote to Washington three days later, "Mr Madison is gaining ground fast but still he is involved in much doubt & difficulty.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The debate that DeRose deemed perhaps the most significant of the race took place one evening at the Hebron Lutheran Church in Culpeper (today in Madison County).
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The Lutherans, like the Baptists, had been persecuted in America, and generally voted as a bloc to maximize their influence.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Monroe and Madison attended the worship service, after which there was musical entertainment featuring fiddles.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] They and the congregation then went outside, and the two candidates debated on the front porch as the congregation stood in the bitter cold, with snow on the ground, likely for hours.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Riding away afterwards, likely home to Montpelier, Madison suffered a frostbitten nose.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] In his old age, former president Madison would tell the story of that night, and point to the left side of his nose, saying he had battle scars.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] White males who were 21 years of age or older and who owned 50 acres (20 ha) of unimproved land or half that with a house were eligible to vote in the Fifth District.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Approximately 5,189 voters formed the district's electorate.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Per the 1790 census, there were 11,231 free white males age over 16 in the district, so about half of free white men were able to vote.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The total population (including women, slaves and children) of the district was 91,007, so the electorate made up less than 6% of the total population, and perhaps 12–15% of those aged over 21.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] There was no secret ballot in Virginia elections in 1789; voters entered the local courthouse and publicly declared their votes, to be recorded by a clerk.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The elections were administered by county sheriffs, normally the senior justice of the peace who had not already served in that capacity.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Due to the bitterly cold weather in the Fifth District, the sheriffs in some counties extended voting beyond February 2, allowing more voters to reach their county courthouse.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] This was not authorized by Virginia law, but had also occurred in the voting for presidential electors the previous month.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] To get out the vote, Madison's supporters sent wagons around to transport voters to the polls.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] They brought one very old man from a distance, and he listened to them talk and asked if the Monroe spoken of was the son of Spence Monroe, formerly of Westmoreland County.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] On being told he was, the man declared he would vote for James Monroe, for "I do not know James Madison", but Spence Monroe had once fed him, clothed him and sheltered him.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Once the polls closed, the local sheriff went to the door of the courthouse and proclaimed the result.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] It took time for complete results to be compiled; partial returns were printed in newspapers.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] On February 10, the sheriffs of the eight counties of the Fifth District met at Albemarle's courthouse, as the county first named in the election statute, to certify the results.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Their returns indicated that Madison won the election with 1,308 votes to 972 for Monroe.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] In Madison's home county of Orange, he received 216 votes to Monroe's 9, in Culpeper 256 to Monroe's 103; he won Albemarle County by 69 votes and Louisa by 104.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison had given considerable attention to Orange, apparently spending the day of the polls there despite the urgings of some supporters to base himself for the day in a more populous county, and two-thirds of his margin of victory came from Orange.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Strong Baptist support for Madison there contributed to the outcome.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison had been able to hold down the margin in strongly Anti-Federalist Amherst to 246–145 for Monroe, who also took his home county of Spotsylvania by 74 votes, Fluvanna by 21 and Goochland by 1 vote.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The Baptists favored Madison due to his record of support for religious liberty.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] After the election, Madison wrote to Jefferson, "It was my misfortune to be thrown into a contest with our friend, Col.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The occasion produced considerable efforts among our respective friends.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] According to Stewart, "Barely thirty years old, Monroe had time to make his way.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] In the House of Representatives, Madison introduced and guided to passage the amendments that became known as the Bill of Rights.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He broke with Washington over the administration's policies, and allied with Jefferson, helping gain the latter's election to the presidency, and became his Secretary of State in 1801.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He succeeded Jefferson as president in 1809.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Although defeated for Congress, Monroe's frequent court appearances as a lawyer kept him in the public eye in Virginia.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] In 1790, after Grayson's death, the General Assembly elected him to the U.S.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He served thereafter in a number of offices, including, twice, Governor of Virginia, and in 1811 Madison named Monroe as Secretary of State.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Monroe was elected president in succession to Madison in 1816, taking office the following year.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] The **1790–91 United States Senate elections** were held on various dates in various states.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Senate elections occurred during the first midterm election cycle, which took place in the middle of President George Washington's first term.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] As these elections were prior to the ratification of the Seventeenth Amendment in 1913, senators were chosen by state legislatures.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Senators were elected over a wide range of time throughout 1790 and 1791, and a seat may have been filled months late or remained vacant due to legislative deadlock.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] In these elections, terms were up for the nine senators in Class 1.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] After the June 25, 1790 elections in Rhode Island.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Except if/when noted, the number following candidates is the whole number vote(s), not a percentage.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] In these elections, the winners were seated before March 4, 1791; ordered by election date.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] In these regular elections, the winners were seated March 4, 1791; ordered by state.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] All of these elections involved the Class 1 seats.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] In these elections, the winners were seated after March 4, 1791, the beginning of the next Congress.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] All of the senators from Connecticut were Pro-Administration through 1795.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Oliver Ellsworth was re-elected in 1791.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] William Samuel Johnson resigned March 3, 1791, at the end of the 1st Congress and Roger Sherman was elected June 13, 1791, to finish the term.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Charles Carroll won re-election over Uriah Forrest by a margin of 20.00%, or 15 votes, for the Class 1 seat.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Senator, Tristam Dalton sought re-election but was eliminated before the third ballot.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] The third ballot saw the election of George Cabot, who had been a member of the Massachusetts Provincial Congress.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] The election in New York was held January 19, 1791, by the New York State Legislature.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Incumbent Philip Schuyler's term would expire March 3, 1791.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] At the State election in April 1790, nominal Federalist majorities were elected to both houses of the 14th New York State Legislature, but many Federalists were friendly to the Democratic-Republican Governor George Clinton, party lines not being drawn very strictly then.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] The incumbent Philip Schuyler ran for re-election as the candidate of the Federalist Party.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] New York State Attorney General Aaron Burr was the candidate of the Democratic-Republican Party, but was at that time a rather moderate politician, opposing the ultras of both parties.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Burr was the choice of both the State Senate and the State Assembly, and was declared elected.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Schuyler was defeated despite the nominal majority of his party.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Many of the Federalists took the opportunity to show their disapproval of both Schuyler's haughtiness and the financial policies of Alexander Hamilton, the U.S.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Secretary of the Treasury and Schuyler's son-in-law.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Besides, the Livingston faction of the Federalist Party felt betrayed after the election of Rufus King over their candidate James Duane in 1789, and now allied themselves with Clinton and later became Democratic-Republicans.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Obs.: Burr had a majority of 5 votes in the Assembly, but the exact number of votes is unclear.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] In 1791, the legislature failed to elect due to a disagreement on procedure.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] The seat would remain vacant until 1793.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Bradley and Moses Robinson were elected by the Vermont House of Representatives and Governor and Council in January 1791, anticipating Vermont's admission to the union.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Vermont was admitted as the 14th state on March 4, 1791.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] The Senate had adjourned on March 3, at the completion of the 1st United States Congress; the 2nd United States Congress held a one-day session on March 4, and was not scheduled to convene again until October 24.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] As a result of this congressional schedule Bradley and Robinson had not been seated when the Vermont House of Representatives convened in early October, 1791.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] At this legislative session, some members suggested that the January election of Bradley and Robinson had been premature, since Vermont had not yet been admitted to the union.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Bradley and Robinson volunteered to resign the credentials of their January elections; on October 17, the Governor and Council voted again, and selected Bradley and Robinson.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] The House of Representatives then voted a second time, and also selected Bradley and Robinson.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Bradley was selected for the "short term" (Class 3), which expired on March 3, 1795.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Robinson received the "long term" (Class 1), which expired on March 3, 1797.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] William Grayson died March 12, 1790, and John Walker was appointed to continue the term.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Future President James Monroe was elected in November 1790 to finish the term.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Monroe was re-elected in 1791 to the next term, as well.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] The state of union is an address, in the United States, given by the president to a joint session of Congress, the United States House of Representatives and United States Senate.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] The United States constitution requires the president "from time to time give to the Congress Information of the State of the Union." Today the state of the union address is given as a speech, though this is not a requirement of the constitution.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] George Washington chose to address the Congress in a speech annually; on October 25, 1791, he gave his third speech.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] A major concern at the time was the raising of taxes, as Congress were arguing whether they had the constitutional power to do so.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] Revenues for the Federal Government were at that time mostly collected on import duties.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] Alexander Hamilton, the then Secretary of the Treasury, felt these had been raised to as high a level as was reasonable, and a new income stream was necessary.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] Before the speech, Congress had been debating where to put the capital.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] Finally, through a deal made between Alexander Hamilton, James Madison, and Secretary of State Thomas Jefferson, they came to a conclusion.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] This deal is known as the Compromise of 1790.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] At the time the U.S. was in possession of the original thirteen colonies, along with the land gained in the Treaty of Paris.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] The Treaty of Paris ended the revolutionary war; in it, America was granted territory as far west as the Mississippi River.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] Known as the year of "Great Immigration" 1788 was the year many Americans moved west.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] On October 18, 1790, the Ohio tribe defeated an expedition of American troops near Fort Wayne, Indiana; this signified the beginning of the hostilities in the North West territory.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] On March 30, 1791, construction of the Knoxville Road began, linking to the Wilderness Road and to Knoxville.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] The road opened up more frontier area for settlements.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] In September 1791, there was much hostility in Ohio territory; this caused Americans to build forts at Hamilton, St.Clair, Jefferson, Greenville and Recovery.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] At the time the Census Act had been in place for just over a year and a half.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] The act called for a routine census of the United States, and was passed by Congress on March 1, 1790.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] He acknowledged that there had been some "degree of discontent" about the Whiskey Tax, and that it was not perfect, but he was going to keep it anyway.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] He said "revision of the provision will be found advisable." The Whiskey tax was one Hamilton wanted enacted as part of a funding system for the new country.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] He says that the debt has been mostly dealt with, but there might be a few things that still need to be paid off and he urges the House of Representatives to pay off any lingering debts, and there will be exact numbers coming to them soon.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] "The part of the debt of the United States which remains unsubscribed will naturally engage your further deliberation," Washington is saying the House of Representatives must talk further on the debt that has not yet been dealt with.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] Washington briefly mentions the "completion of the census of the inhabitants," he is talking about the Census of 1790.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] He says that "the present population of the United States borders on 4,000,000 persons".
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] The number was 3,929,625 according to the 1790 Census.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] At the end of the speech he comments on "the militia, the post office and post roads, the mint, weights and measures, a provision for the sale of the vacant lands of the United States." Washington wants to send militia to particularly vulnerable places in the US, as they are a new country.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] He says that the United States must have "systematic and solid arrangements, exposed as little as possible to the hazards of fortuitous circumstances." He beliefs that there must be more post offices and roads, to create unity with in the country.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] As well to make sure that there is no :misrepresentation and misconception" of the "laws and proceedings of the Government." He then remarks that there is a scarcity of smaller American change and that there must be more put into place.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] Washington then goes on to say that the wright and measures of the country must be uniform and conducive to public convenience.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] Washington spent a good deal of the speech trying to convince the Native Americans to become part of the United States, as well as convincing the citizens of the country of the importance of doing so.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] He pushed the Senate to ratify the treaties pending before that House with the Cherokees and Six Nations of Indians (Iroquois Confederation).
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] He stated that the House needed to act on bills to ensure the financial security of the nation.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] The **1792–93 United States Senate elections** were held on various dates in various states, coinciding with President George Washington's unanimous re-election.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] Senate elections were prior to the ratification of the Seventeenth Amendment in 1913, senators were chosen by state legislatures.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] Senators were elected over a wide range of time throughout 1792 and 1793, and a seat may have been filled months late or remained vacant due to legislative deadlock.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] In these elections, terms were up for the ten senators in Class 2.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] Formal organized political parties had yet to form in the United States, but two political factions were present: The coalition of Senators who supported George Washington's administration were known as the Pro-Administration Party, and the Senators against him as the Anti-Administration Party.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] Virginia's elections are considered a single race here.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] After the June 1792 admission of Kentucky.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] Two Pro-Administration senators (Benjamin Hawkins of North Carolina and John Langdon of New Hampshire) changed to Anti-Administration.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] The vacant seat in Pennsylvania was filled February 28, 1793 by an Anti-Administration senator.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] In these elections, the winner was seated before March 4, 1793; ordered by election date.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] In these regular elections, the winner was seated on March 4, 1793; ordered by state.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] All of the elections involved the Class 2 seats.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] In this special election, the winner was seated after March 4, 1793, the beginning of the next Congress.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] One-term Anti-Federalist William Few was defeated by fellow Anti-Federalist, James Jackson.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] Jackson won 24 votes in the Georgia House of Representatives and 11 in the State Senate for a combined total of 35.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] Few won 3 in the House and 2 in the Senate for a combined total of 5.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] Jackson took office as a member of the 3rd United States Congress on March 4, 1793.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] He would later resign in 1795 to run for his state's legislature.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] Incumbent John Brown, who had previously been elected in a special election was easily reelected with no opposition and 100% of votes from the legislators.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] Richard Potts won election to fill the seat vacated by Charles Carroll over Josh Hoskins Stone by a margin of 21.84%, or 19 votes, for the Class 1 seat.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] Senator Paine Wingate was not reelected.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] The New Hampshire General Court instead elected Federalist Samuel Livermore, a U.S.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] Livermore, like his fellow senator, John Langdon, would go on to serve as President Pro-Tempore during this term.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] Pro-Administration Samuel Johnston lost re-election to Anti-Administration Alexander Martin for the class 2 seat.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] The other senator, Benjamin Hawkins, switched his support from Pro- to Anti-Administration.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] There was a special election on February 28, 1793, for the Class 1 seat from Pennsylvania.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] Incumbent William Maclay's term had ended on March 3, 1791, but the legislature failed to elect a successor due to a disagreement on the procedure to be followed in the election.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] The seat remained vacant until Albert Gallatin was elected by the Pennsylvania General Assembly to the seat during this election.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] Upon agreement between the two houses of the Pennsylvania General Assembly, the House of Representatives and the Senate, regarding the procedure to elect a new Senator, an election was finally held on February 28, 1793.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] On February 28, 1794, the Senate determined that Gallatin did not satisfy the citizenship requirement for service and he was removed from office.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] Gallatin was replaced in the Senate by a special election in 1794.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] Anti-Administration senator Richard Henry Lee resigned October 8, 1792, just before the March 3, 1793 end of term.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] Anti-administration John Taylor of Caroline was elected October 18, 1792 to finish Lee's term and then re-elected in 1793 to the next term.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1792-state-of-the-union-address] The **1792 State of the Union Address** was delivered by George Washington to Congress on Tuesday, November 6, 1792.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1792-state-of-the-union-address] It was presented in Philadelphia's Congress Hall.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1792-state-of-the-union-address] The president commented on continued incursions by Native Americans into frontier settlements.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1792-state-of-the-union-address] Notably, the address contains mention of the Chickamaugas, a part of the Cherokee tribe that committed multiple incursions in frontiers along the Tennessee River.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1792-state-of-the-union-address] The President noted that the incursions were a violation of the Treaty of Holston.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1792-state-of-the-union-address] Still further to promote and secure these inestimable ends there is nothing which can have a more powerful tendency than the careful cultivation of harmony, combined with a due regard to stability, in the public councils.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1793-state-of-the-union-address] The **1793 State of the Union Address** was given by George Washington, the first president of the United States.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1793-state-of-the-union-address] It was given in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania at Congress Hall.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1793-state-of-the-union-address] During the address, Washington spoke of Peace through strength.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1793-state-of-the-union-address] He also urged the expansion of the legal code and jurisdiction of the courts in order to enforce the laws of the land.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1793-state-of-the-union-address] The President reported on progress for peace with the Creek and Cherokee tribes and noted that trade with the tribes should be expanded where possible.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1820-state-of-the-union-address] The **1820 State of the Union Address** was delivered by the fifth president of the United States James Monroe to the 16th United States Congress on November 14, 1820.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1820-state-of-the-union-address] In his address, Monroe reflected on the nation's overall prosperity despite some economic pressures and difficulties.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1820-state-of-the-union-address] He acknowledged the impact of international events, particularly the upheavals in Europe and the transition from war to peace, which had affected American commerce and industry.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1820-state-of-the-union-address] Monroe urged vigilance and continued effort to preserve the nation's stability and prosperity, noting the importance of lessons learned from these challenges.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1820-state-of-the-union-address] Monroe highlighted ongoing tensions with Spain over the ratification of the Adams–Onís Treaty, which had yet to be finalized.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1820-state-of-the-union-address] He expressed concerns about efforts to use parts of Florida for smuggling goods into the United States but remained hopeful that an amicable resolution would be reached.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1820-state-of-the-union-address] Monroe also discussed relations with Great Britain and France, particularly trade issues.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1820-state-of-the-union-address] He noted that negotiations with France had encountered difficulties, and a French minister was expected to visit Washington to continue discussions.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1820-state-of-the-union-address] In the meantime, he proposed extending relief to French ships that had entered U.S. ports before the implementation of new tonnage duties.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1820-state-of-the-union-address] On the domestic front, Monroe emphasized the nation's strong financial standing, with a significant reduction of the national debt.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1820-state-of-the-union-address] The public debt had been reduced by over $66 million since 1815, and despite economic difficulties, the government had maintained its expenditures and made progress on important infrastructure projects, such as fortifications along the coast.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1820-state-of-the-union-address] Monroe also reported on efforts to promote the civilization of Native American tribes through trade and settlement programs, noting the importance of maintaining peace with the tribes while encouraging their gradual integration into American society.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1820-state-of-the-union-address] Additionally, he addressed naval operations, including the suppression of piracy and the slave trade, particularly along the Barbary Coast and in the Atlantic.
[src:1820-state-of-the-union-address/1820-state-of-the-union-address] In conclusion, Monroe celebrated the nation's progress and urged continued vigilance in both foreign and domestic affairs to preserve the Union's prosperity and security.
